2026-04-16 12:34:48 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['switched‑cables indicator LED branch (LED and/or series resistor) in control (ambient sensor) module'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show ~12 V at the control input +, but only ~0.36 V at the control output + and on the relay’s ‘low side’, with confirmed low‑ohmic continuity and good relay contacts. The negative rail is continuous and near 0 V. The comparator/driver and relay themselves have been verified good. This means some unintended load inside the control module is drawing current and pulling the supposed +12 V rail down to ~0.36 V before it reaches the relay/output node.\n\nPer the circuit, the only intentional load tied from the switched + line toward 0 V inside the control module is the “switched cables indicator” LED plus its series resistor, connected between the switched output node and the negative rail. If this LED branch has failed short (e.g., LED internally shorted or series resistor shorted/bridged), it would clamp the switched + rail close to ground whenever 12 V is applied, causing the ~0.36 V you observe at the control output +, while still leaving enough voltage at the module input + for the comparator logic to operate. That is exactly the present symptom set: correct 12 V into the module, but no usable 12 V out, and no obvious high resistance in the relay or wiring.\n\nTherefore the most plausible root cause is a fault (short circuit) in the switched‑cables indicator LED branch inside the ambient sensor/control module, effectively shunting the switched + rail to the negative rail and collapsing the voltage to the load.'
